    <div class="earth_container">
        <div class="earth_card" id="earth-structure">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth%27s_structure" target="_blank">Earth's Structure</a></h2>
            <p>The Earth is composed of three main layers: the crust, mantle, and core. 
              The crust is the outermost layer and is divided into tectonic plates that 
              move and interact with each other.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="continents-oceans">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continents_and_oceans" target="_blank">Continents and Oceans</a></h2>
            <p>There are seven continents on Earth: Africa, Antarctica, Asia, Europe, North America, 
              Australia, and South America. The Earth's surface is also covered by five major oceans: the Pacific Ocean, 
              Atlantic Ocean, Indian Ocean, Southern Ocean, and Arctic Ocean.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="weather-climate">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weather" target="_blank">Weather and Climate</a></h2>
            <p>Weather refers to the short-term atmospheric conditions, such as temperature, humidity, wind, and precipitation. 
              Climate, on the other hand, refers to the long-term average weather patterns in a particular region.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="natural-disasters">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_disaster" target="_blank">Natural Disasters</a></h2>
            <p>Earth experiences various natural disasters, including earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, tsunamis, hurricanes, tornadoes, floods, and wildfires. These events can cause significant damage to the environment and pose risks to human populations.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="ecosystems-biodiversity">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecosystem" target="_blank">Ecosystems and Biodiversity</a></h2>
            <p>An ecosystem is a community of living organisms and their interactions with each other and their environment. Earth is home to a vast array of ecosystems, including forests, grasslands, deserts, freshwater systems, and marine environments. Biodiversity refers to the variety of life forms found within these ecosystems, encompassing plants, animals, and microorganisms.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="landforms-geography">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landform" target="_blank">Landforms and Geographical Features</a></h2>
            <p>Earth exhibits diverse landforms and geographical features, such as mountains, valleys, plains, plateaus, canyons, rivers, lakes, and glaciers. These features are shaped by geological processes, including tectonic activity, erosion, and deposition.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="natural-resources">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_resource" target="_blank">Natural Resources</a></h2>
            <p>Earth possesses a variety of natural resources that are essential for human civilization. These resources include minerals, fossil fuels (coal, oil, natural gas), renewable energy sources (solar, wind, hydroelectric), water, forests, and agricultural land.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="environmental-challenges">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environmental_issue" target="_blank">Environmental Challenges</a></h2>
            <p>Earth faces numerous environmental challenges, including climate change, deforestation, pollution (air, water, soil), habitat loss, overpopulation, and species extinction. Addressing these challenges is crucial for the long-term sustainability of our planet.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="earth-history">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Earth" target="_blank">Earth's History</a></h2>
            <p>The Earth is estimated to be around 4.5 billion years old. Throughout its history, Earth has undergone significant geological changes, including the formation of continents, the evolution of life, the impact of asteroid and comet collisions, and the shifting of climate and ecosystems.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="water-cycle">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_cycle" target="_blank">Water Cycle</a></h2>
            <p>The water cycle is the continuous movement of water on, above, and below the Earth's surface. It involves processes such as evaporation, condensation, precipitation, and runoff, which play a vital role in distributing water resources across the planet.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="plate-tectonics">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plate_tectonics" target="_blank">Plate Tectonics</a></h2>
            <p>Plate tectonics is the scientific theory that describes the movement and interaction of the Earth's tectonic plates. It explains the formation of continents, mountain ranges, earthquakes, and volcanic activity.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="earth-magnetic-field">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth%27s_magnetic_field" target="_blank">Earth's Magnetic Field</a></h2>
            <p>The Earth has a magnetic field generated by the movement of molten iron within its outer core. This magnetic field protects the planet from harmful solar radiation and plays a crucial role in navigation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="seasons">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Season" target="_blank">Seasons</a></h2>
            <p>Seasons on Earth are caused by the tilt of the planet's axis in relation to its orbit around the Sun. This tilt leads to variations in sunlight intensity and temperature throughout the year.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="moon">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moon" target="_blank">Earth's Moon</a></h2>
            <p>The Moon is Earth's only natural satellite, orbiting around it at an average distance of about 238,900 miles (384,400 kilometers). The Moon influences tides and has been the subject of exploration and scientific study.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="glaciers">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glacier" target="_blank">Glaciers</a></h2>
            <p>Glaciers are large masses of ice that form on land and move slowly under their own weight. They shape the landscape, carve out valleys, and play a crucial role in Earth's water cycle.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="fossils-paleontology">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fossil" target="_blank">Fossils and Paleontology</a></h2>
            <p>Fossils are the preserved remains or traces of ancient plants and animals. Paleontology is the scientific study of fossils, providing insights into past life forms and Earth's history.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="earth-ecosystem-services">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecosystem_services" target="_blank">Earth's Ecosystem Services</a></h2>
            <p>Ecosystem services are the benefits provided to humans by natural ecosystems. These services include clean air and water, pollination of crops, regulation of climate, nutrient cycling, and recreational opportunities.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="earth-age-geological-time">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Age_of_the_Earth" target="_blank">Earth's Age and Geological Time</a></h2>
            <p>The Earth is estimated to be around 4.5 billion years old. Geological time scales divide Earth's history into different eons, eras, periods, and epochs, based on significant geological and biological events.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="earth_card" id="earth-solar-system">
            <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth" target="_blank">Earth's Place in the Solar System</a></h2>
            <p>Earth is the third planet from the Sun and is part of the inner solar system. It orbits the Sun at an average distance of about 93 million miles (150 million kilometers) and has a unique set of conditions that support life.</p>
        </div>

